{{Otheruseslist|'''The first of the Ten Heavenly Stems'''|other uses|[[Ko (disambiguation)]]}} {{Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches}}
'''Kō''' (甲, also pronounced *Kinoye*) is the **first** of the [[Ten Heavenly Stems]] (*Jikkan*).
In the [[Yin-Yang and Five Elements theory]] (*Onmyō Gogyo Setsu*), it is associated with the **Yang aspect of Wood**, which is why in Japan it is also called *Kinoye* (木の兄, "elder brother of Wood").
## Overview * The **origin of the character "甲"** has been the subject of various theories, but there is **no definitive consensus**.<ref>{{Citation| author=Yu Shengwu (于省吾) | year=1996 | title=甲骨文字詁林 (Jiǎgǔ wénzì gǔlín) | location=Beijing | publisher=Zhonghua Book Company (中華書局) | isbn=7-101-01430-5 | pages=3582–6}}</ref> Its usage in **the Ten Heavenly Stems** derives from **phonetic borrowing** (*kasha* 仮借). * When the **Heavenly Stems** are used **for ranking purposes**, **Kō (甲)** represents **the first position**. Additionally, **"Kō-rui" (甲類) or "Kō-shu" (甲種)** are used as **classification terms**, though they do not necessarily indicate hierarchy. * Years **ending in 4** in the [[Western calendar]] correspond to **the Heavenly Stem of Kō (甲)**. In traditional Chinese calendrical naming, the **name for the year associated with Kō** is **"Apu" (閼逢)** (also written as **"Apong" (閼蓬)** or **"Enpō" (焉逢)**).<ref>{{Cite web |title=<nowiki>辞典検視 [閼逢 : ㄜˋ ㄈㄥˊ]</nowiki> |url=https://dict.revised.moe.edu.tw/dictView.jsp?ID=147004&la=0&powerMode=0 |website=Ministry of Education, Taiwan 《重編國語辭典修訂本》 |access-date=2024-03-08 |language=zh-Hant-TW}}</ref> * In **Chinese chemical nomenclature**, "Kō (甲)" is used to denote **organic compounds with a single carbon atom**, such as **methane (CH₄)** or **methyl groups (-CH₃)**. * The **opposite stem** to **Kō (甲)** is **Ki (己)** (*Tsuchinoe*). * The **lucky direction (Eho, 恵方)** associated with **Kō (甲)** is **East-Northeast, slightly to the East (75°)**.
