{{Otheruseslist|'''The first of the Ten Heavenly Stems'''|other uses|[[Ko (disambiguation)]]}}
{{Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches}}

'''Kō''' (甲) is the first of the {{ill|Ten Heavenly Stems|ja|十干}}.

According to the {{ill|Yin-Yang and Five Elements theory|ja|陰陽五行説}}, it is associated with the yang aspect of the {{ill|wood element|ja|木}}, and in Japan, it is referred to as "{{ill|kinoe|ja|きのえ}}" (elder wood).

== Overview ==
* The origin of the character "甲" has been the subject of various proposals, but no definitive theory has been established.<ref>{{Citation| author=于省吾| year=1996| title=甲骨文字誁林| location=Beijing| publisher=中華書局| isbn=7-101-01430-5| pages=3582–6}}</ref> Its use as a term to denote the first of the Ten Heavenly Stems is due to {{ill|phonetic loan|ja|仮借}}.
* When used for ranking, "Kō" signifies the first position. Additionally, it is used in classification names such as "{{ill|Kōrui|ja|甲類}}" and "{{ill|Kōshu|ja|甲種}}," though these do not necessarily indicate superiority in rank.
* In the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|西暦}}, years ending with the digit 4 are considered "Kō" years. The alternative name for the year is "{{ill|Afu|ja|閼逢}}" (also written as "{{ill|Appō|ja|閼蓬}}" or "{{ill|Enpō|ja|焉逢}}").<ref>{{Cite web |title=<nowiki>Dictionary Entry [閼逢: アツホウ]</nowiki> |url=https://dict.revised.moe.edu.tw/dictView.jsp?ID=147004&la=0&powerMode=0 |website=Ministry of Education Revised Chinese Dictionary 2021 |access-date=2024-03-08 |language=zh-Hant-TW}}</ref>
* In {{ill|Chinese chemical nomenclature|ja|化合物命名法}}, it is used to denote compounds and {{ill|functional groups|ja|官能基}} containing one carbon atom, such as {{ill|methane|ja|メタン}} and {{ill|methyl group|ja|メチル基}}.
* Its opposite counterpart is {{ill|Ki (己)|ja|己}} (tsuchinoto).
* The {{ill|lucky direction|ja|恵方}} associated with Kō is slightly east of northeast (75 degrees).

